<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06128145 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06128145 </ACCESS><CAPTION>  Photo; PHOTO: Associated Press; ON GUARD -- A Yugoslav army officer guards aSerbian village where 12 Croatian police officers were killed Thursday.  </CAPTION><DESCRIPT>  YUGOSLAVIA; CIVIL; VIOLENCE; MILITARY; REGULATION; PLANNING  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  The Yugoslav national army has warned that it will step in to restore order ifcivil authorities fail to stem a widening crisis that led to the killing onMonday of a young military policeman during angry anti-army protests in thecoastal city of Split.;    Declaring that Yugoslav society has already enteredcivil war, the statement issued by Veljko Kadijezic, the federal commander,said he has given orders to raise combat readiness and mobilize units torespond to the ethnic violence, which last week flared again in the regions ofthe Croatian republic that are occupied by Serbs.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Front  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  YUGOSLAV ARMY MAY ACT TO END UNREST  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     The killing of a 19-year-old draftee during the Split protest prompted anemergency session of the federal presidency that is to continue today.;    Theeight-man presidency, which this year balked at the army's request to declaremartial law, issued a statement saying it shared the &quot;justified revulsion&quot; atthe protest.;    The presidency said the &quot;main culprits are those who calledfor the actions,&quot; which was seen as a veiled reference to President FranjoTudjman of Croatia, who on Sunday suggested a protest against the army.;   About 30,000 people stormed the main military building in Split to protest thearmy's failure to break a blockade sealing off the predominantly Croatianvillage of Kijevo, the Yugoslav press agency Tanyug reported.;    Kijevo,surrounded by rebellious Serbian villages, has been virtually cut off byroadblocks since April 28, despite promises that the army, in position to keepthe peace, would clear the way for trucks carrying food and medicine.;    Theprotest in Split, a tourist center on the Dalmatian coast, was a turning pointin the violence that has plagued the republic since last summer, when Serbsliving in Croatia first challenged the new government in Zagreb with demandsfor greater autonomy.;    Until now, the violence was mostly confined toregions where Serbs and Croats, two nations divided by a history of hatred andrevenge, live in close proximity.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  New York Times  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><CITY>  Zagreb, Yugoslavia  </CITY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910507  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Tuesday  </DAY><MONTH>  May  </MONTH><PG.COL>  14A  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><FEATURE>  PHOTO  </FEATURE><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  349  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Tuesday May 7, 199100128145,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>